Conceptual¶

Question 1¶

Describe the null hypotheses to which the p-values given in the table (see below). Explain what conclusions you can draw based on these p-values. Your explanation should be phrased in terms of sales, TV, radio, and newspaper, rather than in terms of the coefficients of the linear model.

Coefficient Std. error t-statistics p-value
Intercept 2.939 0.3119 9.42 <0.0001
TV 0.046 0.0014 32.81 <0.0001
Radio 0.189 0.0086 21.89 <0.0001
Newspaper -0.001 0.0059 -0.18 0.8599

Null hypothesis here is that there is no relationship between the considered variable (Intercept, TV, Radio, Newspaper given by X) and Sales (Y). In other words it means we have $\hat{β}_{Intercept} = 0 $ for first row, $\hat{β}_{TV} = 0 $ for second row, $\hat{β}_{Radio} = 0 $ for third row, $\hat{β}_{Newspaper} = 0 $ for fourth row as Null Hypothesis.

Model : $Y = β_{0} + β_{TV}X_{TV} + β_{Radio}X_{Radio} + β_{NewsPaper}X_{NewsPaper} + ϵ$

Conclusions¶
  • Intercept 2.939 shows the value of sales when there is no advertising in TV, Radio or Newspaper. When we have a unit of TV advertisement, then we can increase the sales by 0.046 units. Similarly when there is a unit of Radio advertisement, then we can increase the sales by 0.189. As for newspaper, it says the sales readuce by 0.001 unit. But we can see this coefficient is not statitically significant as p-value is 0.85
  • Intercept, TV, Radio seems to have a significant effect on Sales. But Newspaper seems to be having almost no effect on sales as the p value is much higher. Hence advertisement in TV and radio seems to increase the sales significantly while Newspaper advertisement seems to have no effect in sales. This may or may not be true as we have assumed that the variable are independent (no interactions) as we use multiple regression model to find the coefficients. If the assumptions of the model is wrong, then the results will obviously can be wrong.

Question 2¶

Assume that you collected a dataset of 100 observations containing a single predictor and a quantitative response. Then, you decided to fit a

(i) linear regression model to the data, as well as a separate

(ii) cubic regression, i.e. $Y = β_{0} + β_{1}X^{1} + β_{2}X^{2} + β_{3}X^{3} + ϵ$

a) Suppose that the true relationship between $X$ and $Y$ is linear, i.e. $Y = β_{0} + β_{1}X + ϵ$. Consider the training residual sum of squares (RSS) for the linear regression, and also the training RSS for the cubic regression. Would we expect one to be lower than the other, would we expect them to be the same, or is there not enough information to tell? Justify your answer¶

We can expect the cubic regression to show less training RSS. This is because cubic regression has higher complexity and very easily result in overfitting. That is, cubic regression result in model with very high variance and low bias. The linear regression will have less variance, and will not fit the training data perfectly resulting in more error.

b) Answer part (a) using the test RSS rather than training RSS.¶

We would expect linear regression to have less test RSS. This is because linear regression is less complex and will result in model having less variance compared to cubic regression. Also note that we have 100 observations with just one predictor ($ n >> p $). This usually means linear regression will learn the true linear relationship between $X$ and $Y$ with good efficiency. This will result in less bias as true model is very close to predicted model resulting in very less test RSS. But for cubic regression, test RSS will be greater because of high variance.

c) Suppose that the true relationship between $X$ and $Y$ is not linear. However, we don’t know how far it is from linear. Consider the training RSS for the linear regression, and also the training RSS for the cubic regression. Would we expect one to be lower than the other, would we expect them to be the same, or is there not enough information to tell? Justify your answer.¶

In general, I would expect cubic regression to show lower training RSS. This is because, when we have more complex the model, we get more variance. Thus high variance model will result in overfitting more training observations resulting in less training RSS. Linear regression will result in high amount of error because it cannot capture the correct underlying pattern or any noises in the data.

d) Answer (c) using test RSS rather than training RSS.¶

In general, linear model will have more bias and less variance, while cubic regression will have less bias and more variance. But considering that the true relationship between $X$ and $Y$ is not linear, We can say the model which is closer to true relationship have less test RSS. If the model is too away from linear relationship, then linear model will not be able to learn the general pattern in the dataset resulting in errors due to high bias of linear model. Similarly if the true model is very close to linear model, then high variance of cubic regression will result in high amount of error in test RSS for cubic regression. Hence there is not enough information to answer the question. We need to know which model is closer to orginal model to conlcude which model will reselt in low test RSS.

Question 3¶

a) Discuss the implications that uncertainty in $X$ would have on parameter estimates based on linear regression models. Should we care about error in $X$ when fitting OLS regressions?¶

Error in X will cause Regression dilution where the parameter estimates are underestimated. As Uncertainty in $X$ increases, the relationship between $X$ and $Y$ becomes weak and hence slope(parameter) decreses. Therefore the $ \hat{\beta}_1 $ value decreases from the true value resulting in Regression dilution. Hence we should care about error in $X$ as more error means highly underestimated value of $ \hat{\beta}_1 $ . Another issue efficiency of the estimators will be reduced because of this. Measurement error in X can lead to incorrect conclusions in hypothesis testing because the regression dilution causes the predicted parameters to go to zero.

b) Provide a brief discussion on the concept of regression dilution.¶

Regression dilution occurs when there is measurement error in the independent variable (X) in a regression model. This error can lead to underestimation of the true relationship between X and the dependent variable (Y). This attenuation of the slope coefficient is due to the fact that the measured values of X are imperfectly correlated with the true values of X, leading to an underestimate of the true effect of X on Y.To mitigate the effects of regression dilution, researchers can use methods such as instrumental variables, measurement error models, or robust standard errors, depending on the nature of the measurement error and the research question at hand.

The least squares estimates in ordinary least squares (OLS) for the model $ y = \beta_1 X + \beta_0 $ can be expressed as:

$ \hat{\beta}_1 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i - \bar{x})(y_i - \bar{y})}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (x_i - \bar{x})^2} = \frac{Cov(X,Y)}{Var(X)}$

$ \hat{\beta}_0 = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta}_1 \bar{x} $

Where:

  • $ \hat{\beta}_1 $ is the estimated intercept,
  • $ \hat{\beta}_0 $ is the estimated slope,
  • $ x_i $ and $ y_i $ are the observed values,
  • $ \bar{x} $ and $ \bar{y} $ are the means of the observed values.

Suppose the $\widetilde{X} = X + w$. where w is the error in $X$. On simplification we can show that the $ \hat{\beta}_1^{'} = \hat{\beta}_1 \frac{Var(X)}{Var(X) + Var(w)} $. Where we assume $w$ and $X$ are independent and $E[w] = 0$ . We can see that the slope becomes low as we error variance increases. This behaviour is called regression dilution.

c) Are there any linear regression models that account for uncertainty in $X$ and $Y$? Please do some independent research and cite your sources.¶

  • Errors-in-variables models or measurement error models are regression models that account for measurement errors in the independent variables. In contrast, standard regression models assume that those regressors have been measured exactly, or observed without error; as such, those models account only for errors in the dependent variables, or responses Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Errors-in-variables_models
  • Total Least Squares Regression (TLS): TLS is a regression technique that minimizes the perpendicular distances from the data points to the regression line, rather than just the vertical distances as in ordinary least squares (OLS). This method accounts for errors in both X and Y variables. Ref: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_least_squares
  • Deming regression is an errors-in-variables model that tries to find the line of best fit for a two-dimensional data set. Ref: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deming_regression

d) Distinguish between least squares and maximum likelihood in the context of linear regression models¶

Least squares is a specific method for estimating the parameters of a linear regression model by minimizing the sum of squared residuals, while maximum likelihood is a more general statistical approach that aims to find the parameter values that make the observed data most likely under the assumed model.

In the context of linear regression models, least squares and maximum likelihood are two different methods used to estimate the parameters of the model.

Least Squares (LS):

  • Objective: Minimizes the sum of the squared differences between the observed values of the dependent variable (Y) and the values predicted by the linear regression model.
  • Estimation: Estimates the parameters (coefficients) of the regression model that minimize the sum of squared residuals.
  • Advantages: Simple to implement, computationally efficient, and has closed-form solutions for parameter estimation.
  • Disadvantages: Assumes normally distributed errors, sensitive to outliers, and does not provide a measure of uncertainty in the parameter estimates.

Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE):

  • Objective: Maximizes the likelihood function, which measures the probability of observing the given data under the assumed statistical model.
  • Estimation: Estimates the parameters of the regression model that maximize the likelihood function, making the observed data most probable under the assumed model.
  • Advantages: Provides a more flexible framework that can accommodate different error distributions, provides measures of uncertainty (standard errors) for the parameter estimates, and allows for hypothesis testing using likelihood ratio tests.
  • Disadvantages: Can be computationally intensive, especially for complex models and large datasets, and requires specifying a probability distribution for the errors.

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = df_processed['horsepower']
y = df_processed['mpg']
# Add a constant to the predictor variable X
X = sm.add_constant(X)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=42)



# Fit the linear regression model
model = sm.OLS(y_train, X_train).fit()

# Print the summary of the model
model.summary()

V. Now, please briefly explain the main use of inverse predictions. List at least two practical examples.¶

Inverse prediction, also known as back prediction or prediction in the reverse direction, is a statistical method used to estimate the value of an independent variable (predictor) based on a known value of the dependent variable (response) and the regression model.

The main use of inverse predictions is to estimate the value of the independent variable when only the dependent variable is known. This can be useful in various scenarios, such as:

  1. Quality control: In manufacturing, if a product fails a quality test and the dependent variable (e.g., strength, durability) is known, inverse prediction can be used to estimate the value of the independent variable (e.g., temperature, pressure) that led to the failure. This information can help identify and correct the root cause of the problem.

  2. Environmental monitoring: In environmental studies, if the concentration of a pollutant in a water body exceeds a certain threshold (dependent variable), inverse prediction can be used to estimate the likely source or causes of the pollution (independent variables such as emission levels, waste disposal practices) based on the regression model. This information can guide mitigation efforts and policy decisions.

# BEGIN SOLUTION
from scipy.optimize import fsolve

def regression_function(horsepower, const, coef, mpg):
    return const + coef * horsepower - mpg

mpg_predicted = 24.531987617801335

const = 39.9844
coef = -0.1577	


initial_guess = 10  
horsepower_inferred = fsolve(regression_function, initial_guess, args=(const, coef, mpg_predicted))[0]

print(f"Inferred horsepower for predicted mpg {mpg_predicted}: {horsepower_inferred:.2f}")

# END SOLUTION

The last line corresponds to creating a linear model in which $y$ is a function of $x_1$ and $x_2$. Write out the form of the linear model. What are the regression coefficients?

The linear model can be written as: $ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \varepsilon $ where $\beta_0 = 2$, $\beta_1 = 2$, and $\beta_2 = 0.3$. The regression coefficients are $\beta_0 = 1.958, \beta_1 = 1.924, \beta_2 = 0.307$.

In other words we can write it as $ y = 2 + 2 x_1 + 0.3 x_2 + \varepsilon $

(f) Do the results obtained in (c)–(e) contradict each other? Explain your answer.¶

The actual equation is $ y = 2 + 2 x_1 + 0.3 x_2 + \varepsilon_1 $ and $x_2 = 0.5 * x_1 + \varepsilon_2 $,

For model with only x1, actual equation becomes $ y = 2 + 2 x_1 + 0.3 (0.5 x_1 + \varepsilon_2) + \varepsilon_1 $ i.e, $ y = 2 + 2 x_1 + 0.15 * x_1 + 0.3 \varepsilon_2 + \varepsilon_1 = 2 + 2.15 x_1 + \varepsilon$, Also note that error also increases, when we did this change. Considering the higher error, the predicted model seems to be close enough to be considered as correct.

Similarly for $x_2$, $ y = 2 + 2.15 (\frac{x_2 - \varepsilon_1}{0.5}) + \varepsilon = 2 + 4.3 x_2 + \varepsilon$, Which is again correct as the predicted value is close to real value.

Also note that, for models with only $x_1$ ([1.176, 2.578]) and only $x_2$ ([2.329, 4.794]) , we can see that the actual true coefficients are within the confidence intervel.

But in general we can say that the outlier is not having too high leverage when compared to other points.

Question 8¶

It is claimed that in the case of simple linear regression of $Y$ onto $X$, the $R^2$ statistic is equal to the square of the correlation between $X$ and $Y$. Generate some synthetic data and show that this is the case.

link to correlation function: https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.corrcoef.html

In [64]:
# BEGIN SOLUTION
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = np.random.rand(100)
Y = 2 * x + np.random.normal(0, 0.1, 100)

corr_coef = np.corrcoef(x, Y)[0, 1]

X = sm.add_constant(x)
model = sm.OLS(Y, X).fit()
print(model.summary())
R_squared = model.rsquared
Y_pred = model.predict(X)

print("Correlation coefficient:", corr_coef)
print("Square of Correlation coefficient:", corr_coef*corr_coef)
print("R-squared:", R_squared)

# Plot the data and the regression line
plt.scatter(x, Y)
plt.plot(x, Y_pred, color='red')
plt.xlabel('X')
plt.ylabel('Y')
plt.title('Simple Linear Regression')
plt.show()
